{"title_page": "C.A. Quintet", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = C.A. Quintet\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| genre            = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[acid rock]]\n| years_active     = 1966\u20131971\n| label            = [[Candyfloss Records]]<br>[[Sundazed]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{url|www.caquintet.com}}\n| past_members     = Ken Erwin<br>Doug Reynolds<br>Tom Pohling<br>Rick Patrin<br>Jim Erwin<br>Donnie Chapin<br> Rick Johnson<br>Paul Samuels<br>Toni Crockett\n}}\n\n'''The C.A. Quintet''', from [[Minnesota]], USA, was a [[psychedelic rock]] band active in the late 1960s. They failed to gain national notoriety during their heyday (all their records were locally produced in Minneapolis and none had national distribution). Their only LP released during the band's existence, [[Trip Thru Hell]], sold fewer than 1000 copies and was virtually unheard of outside of their home town. Despite its minuscule initial distribution, the record slowly gained popularity over the next twenty years among collectors and musicians. Due to increasing demand, it was re-released in the early 1980s, by \"Rape an Ape Records\", then released on CD in 1994, on the Sundazed label, including their singles and unreleased material. A live album was released in 1986 of their last performance as a group, re-released in 2006 with additional material, by Swordfish Records U.K...\u2026   An ORIGINAL 1969 CANDY FLOSS RELEASE OFTHIS ALBUM SOLD FOR $5655 on August 17 2014\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* [[Trip Thru Hell]] (LP - 1969)\n* [[Live 1971]] (LP - 1984)\n* [[Last trip at Lake Pepin]] (LP - 2006)\n==== Trip Thru Hell ====\n''Trip Thru Hell'' was a 1968 album by the C.A. Quintet. Locally produced in Minneapolis, less than 500 copies were sold in its original pressing on the Candy Floss label.  Two unauthorized versions have been reissued, an LP on the British ''Psycho'' (illegally) label in 1983 with a stereo channel missing, and a (illegal) 1993 CD by the French ''Eva'' label. Both these releases are missing one track.  The album was finally legally reissued by [[Sundazed Records]] in both [[CD]] (1995) and 2x[[LP album|LP]] (1996) formats, with additional tracks and extensive liner notes.\n\n'''Track Listing'''\n# Trip Thru Hell, Pt. 1 (Erwin) - 9:09\n# Colorado Mourning (Erwin)- 2:31\n# Cold Spider - (Erwin) O4:41\n# Underground Music (Erwin) - 4:43\n# Sleepy Hollow Lane (Erwin) - 2:04\n# Smooth As Silk (Erwin) - 2:12\n# Trip Thru Hell, (Erwin) Pt. 2 - 3:40\n# Dr. Of Philosophy (Erwin) - 2:09\n# Blow To My Soul (Sandler) - 1:59\n# Ain't No Doubt About it (Erwin) - 2:31\n# Mickey's Monkey (Dozier, Holland, Holland) - 2:26\n# I Put A Spell On You (Hawkins) - 2:47\n# I Shot The King (Erwin)- 2:22\n# Fortune Teller's Lie (Erwin) - 2:09\n# Sadie Lavone - (Erwin) 2:49\n# Bury Me In A Marijuana Field (Erwin) - 2:11\n# Colorado Mourning (Alternate Version) (Erwin) - 2:13\n# Underground Music (Alternate Version) (Erwin)- 2:08\n# Smooth As Silk (Alternate Version) (Erwin) - 3:20\n\nAll titles by Ken Erwin except where indicated.\n\n===Singles===\n* Mickey's Monkey/I Want You To Love Me Girl (1967)\n* Smooth As Silk/Dr. Of Philosophy (1968)\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110718160150/http://www.zoom-in.com/blog/music/katie-camosy/a-trip-thru-hell-with-the-ca-quintet] a blog about ''A Trip Thru Hell''\n* [http://www.midwesttribute.com/ca.html] MidwestTribute website, since 2000.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCvqZPwSi0RfeZQWX1V1IMdA\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American psychedelic rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1966]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1971]]\n[[Category:1971 disestablishments in Minnesota]]\n\n\n{{US-rock-band-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = C.A. Quintet\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = group_or_band\n| origin           = [[Minneapolis\u2013Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]], United States\n| genre            = [[Psychedelic rock]], [[acid rock]]\n| years_active     = 1966\u20131971\n| label            = [[Candyfloss Records]]<br>[[Sundazed]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{url|www.caquintet.com}}\n| past_members     = Ken Erwin<br>Doug Reynolds<br>Tom Pohling<br>Rick Patrin<br>Jim Erwin<br>Donnie Chapin<br> Rick Johnson<br>Paul Samuels<br>Toni Crockett\n}}\n\n'''The C.A. Quintet''', from [[Minnesota]], USA, was a [[psychedelic rock]] band active in the late 1960s. They failed to gain national notoriety during their heyday (all their records were locally produced in Minneapolis and none had national distribution). Their only LP released during the band's existence, [[Trip Thru Hell]], sold fewer than 1000 copies and was virtually unheard of outside of their home town. Despite its minuscule initial distribution, the record slowly gained popularity over the next twenty years among collectors and musicians. Due to increasing demand, it was re-released in the early 1980s, by \"Rape an Ape Records\", then released on CD in 1994, on the Sundazed label, including their singles and unreleased material. A live album was released in 1986 of their last performance as a group, re-released in 2006 with additional material, by Swordfish Records U.K...\u2026   An ORIGINAL 1969 CANDY FLOSS RELEASE OFTHIS ALBUM SOLD FOR $5655 on August 17 2014\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n* [[Trip Thru Hell]] (LP - 1969)\n* [[Live 1971]] (LP - 1984)\n* [[Last trip at Lake Pepin]] (LP - 2006)\n==== Trip Thru Hell ====\n''Trip Thru Hell'' was a 1968 album by the C.A. Quintet. Locally produced in Minneapolis, less than 500 copies were sold in its original pressing on the Candy Floss label.  Two unauthorized versions have been reissued, an LP on the British ''Psycho'' (illegally) label in 1983 with a stereo channel missing, and a (illegal) 1993 CD by the French ''Eva'' label. Both these releases are missing one track.  The album was finally legally reissued by [[Sundazed Records]] in both [[CD]] (1995) and 2x[[LP album|LP]] (1996) formats, with additional tracks and extensive liner notes.\n\n'''Track Listing'''\n# Trip Thru Hell, Pt. 1 (Erwin) - 9:09\n# Colorado Mourning (Erwin)- 2:31\n# Cold Spider - (Erwin) O4:41\n# Underground Music (Erwin) - 4:43\n# Sleepy Hollow Lane (Erwin) - 2:04\n# Smooth As Silk (Erwin) - 2:12\n# Trip Thru Hell, (Erwin) Pt. 2 - 3:40\n# Dr. Of Philosophy (Erwin) - 2:09\n# Blow To My Soul (Sandler) - 1:59\n# Ain't No Doubt About it (Erwin) - 2:31\n# Mickey's Monkey (Dozier, Holland, Holland) - 2:26\n# I Put A Spell On You (Hawkins) - 2:47\n# I Shot The King (Erwin)- 2:22\n# Fortune Teller's Lie (Erwin) - 2:09\n# Sadie Lavone - (Erwin) 2:49\n# Bury Me In A Marijuana Field (Erwin) - 2:11\n# Colorado Mourning (Alternate Version) (Erwin) - 2:13\n# Underground Music (Alternate Version) (Erwin)- 2:08\n# Smooth As Silk (Alternate Version) (Erwin) - 3:20\n\nAll titles by Ken Erwin except where indicated.\n\n===Singles===\n* Mickey's Monkey/I Want You To Love Me Girl (1967)\n* Blow to My Soul/She's Got To Be True (1967)\n* Smooth As Silk/Dr. Of Philosophy (1968)\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110718160150/http://www.zoom-in.com/blog/music/katie-camosy/a-trip-thru-hell-with-the-ca-quintet] a blog about ''A Trip Thru Hell''\n* [http://www.midwesttribute.com/ca.html] MidwestTribute website, since 2000.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/channel/UCvqZPwSi0RfeZQWX1V1IMdA\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Musical groups from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:American psychedelic rock music groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1966]]\n[[Category:1966 establishments in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1971]]\n[[Category:1971 disestablishments in Minnesota]]\n\n\n{{US-rock-band-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Keneboy111", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSingles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C.A._Quintet"}
{"title_page": "The Occupied Times of London", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Occupied Times of London\n| logo = Occupied Times of London Logo.jpg\n| image = \n| caption = \n| type = [[Quarterly]] newspaper\n| format = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners = \n| founder = \n| publisher = \n| editor = The OT Collective\n| president = \n| chiefeditor =\n| assoceditor = \n| maneditor =\n| advertisingdirector = \n| newseditor = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| campuseditor = \n| campuschief = \n| opeditor = \n| sportseditor = \n| photoeditor = \n| staff = \n| foundation = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|10|26}}\n| political = [[Autonomist]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| ceased publication = 2017\n| relaunched = \n| headquarters = \n| circulation =\n| sister newspapers = \n| ISSN = \n| oclc = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.theoccupiedtimes.org}}\n| free = \n| dirinteractive = \n}}\n\n'''''The Occupied Times of London''''' was a political newspaper which originated from [[Occupy LSX]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=48132&c=1|title=St Paul's protesters publish newspaper|accessdate=2 November 2011|work=Press Gazette|date=28 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psfk.com/2011/10/protesters-launch-the-occupied-times-of-london-newspaper.html|title=Protesters Launch The Occupied Times of London Newspaper|accessdate=2 November 2011|publisher=PSFK|date=28 October 2011}}</ref> Originally produced from the occupations at St. Paul\u2019s and Finsbury Square, the paper included news, features and interviews. It was a free, non-profit publication without any advertising and was first published on Wednesday 26 October 2011.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/10/26/occupy-london-the-first-e_n_1032909.html \"Occupy London: The First Edition Of The Occupied Times Hits The Presses.\"] [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk The Huffington Post (United Kingdom)]. Accessed November 2011.</ref>\n\nThe design of the Occupied Times of London incorporated [[Jonathan Barnbrook]]'s 'Bastard' font, with a signature back-page placard design or slogan in each issue.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/blog/2012/jan/23/designer-occupy-london-logo-jonathan-barnbrook | title=The Guardian | work=The Guardian| accessdate=7 April 2012 | location=London | first=Paul | last=Owen | date=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe last issue was Issue 29 March 2017 before it became Base Magazine.<ref>http://www.basepublication.org/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GeamBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|title=''Visual Media and Culture of 'Occupy'''|pages=98\u2013101}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=GeamBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA41 ''Visual Media and Culture of \u0091Occupy'']. p.&nbsp;41.\n* {{cite web|url=http://eu.greekreporter.com/2012/01/13/greek-graphic-designers-behind-the-occupied-london-times-paper/|title=Greek Graphic Designers Behind 'The Occupied London Times' Paper|author=Stella Tsolakidou|work=[[Greek Reporter]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.theoccupiedtimes.org Official website]\n\n{{Occupy movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occupied Times of London, The}}\n[[Category:2011 in London]]\n[[Category:Occupy movement in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Occupied Times of London\n| logo = Occupied Times of London Logo.jpg\n| image = \n| caption = \n| type = [[Quarterly]] newspaper\n| format = [[Broadsheet]]\n| owners = \n| founder = \n| publisher = \n| editor = The OT Collective\n| president = \n| chiefeditor =\n| assoceditor = \n| maneditor =\n| advertisingdirector = \n| newseditor = \n| managingeditordesign = \n| campuseditor = \n| campuschief = \n| opeditor = \n| sportseditor = \n| photoeditor = \n| staff = \n| foundation = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|10|26}}\n| political = [[Autonomist]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| ceased publication = 2017\n| relaunched = \n| headquarters = \n| circulation =\n| sister newspapers = \n| ISSN = \n| oclc = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.theoccupiedtimes.org}}\n| free = \n| dirinteractive = \n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2011}}\n\n'''''The Occupied Times of London''''' was a political newspaper which originated from [[Occupy LSX]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=1&storycode=48132&c=1|title=St Paul's protesters publish newspaper|accessdate=2 November 2011|work=Press Gazette|date=28 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.psfk.com/2011/10/protesters-launch-the-occupied-times-of-london-newspaper.html|title=Protesters Launch The Occupied Times of London Newspaper|accessdate=2 November 2011|publisher=PSFK|date=28 October 2011}}</ref> Originally produced from the occupations at St. Paul\u2019s and Finsbury Square, the paper included news, features and interviews. It was a free, non-profit publication without any advertising and was first published on Wednesday 26 October 2011.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/10/26/occupy-london-the-first-e_n_1032909.html \"Occupy London: The First Edition Of The Occupied Times Hits The Presses.\"] [http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk The Huffington Post (United Kingdom)]. Accessed November 2011.</ref>\n\nThe design of the Occupied Times of London incorporated [[Jonathan Barnbrook]]'s 'Bastard' font, with a signature back-page placard design or slogan in each issue.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/blog/2012/jan/23/designer-occupy-london-logo-jonathan-barnbrook | title=The Guardian | work=The Guardian| accessdate=7 April 2012 | location=London | first=Paul | last=Owen | date=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe last issue was Issue 29 March 2017 before it became Base Magazine.<ref>http://www.basepublication.org/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GeamBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA98|title=''Visual Media and Culture of 'Occupy'''|pages=98\u2013101}}\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=GeamBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA41 ''Visual Media and Culture of \u0091Occupy'']. p.&nbsp;41.\n* {{cite web|url=http://eu.greekreporter.com/2012/01/13/greek-graphic-designers-behind-the-occupied-london-times-paper/|title=Greek Graphic Designers Behind 'The Occupied London Times' Paper|author=Stella Tsolakidou|work=[[Greek Reporter]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.theoccupiedtimes.org Official website]\n\n{{Occupy movement}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Occupied Times of London, The}}\n[[Category:2011 in London]]\n[[Category:Occupy movement in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Political newspapers published in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "EngvarB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Occupied_Times_of_London"}
{"title_page": "Edison Awards", "text_new": "{{For|the Dutch award given for musical achievement|Edison Award}}\n{{advert|date=September 2018}}\nEstablished in 1987, the Edison Best New Product Awards\u2122 is an annual competition honoring excellence in innovation in a broad range of categories. \u00a0Known as \u201cthe Oscars of Innovation,\u201d the [https://edisonawards.com/ Edison Awards\u2122] have recognized and honored some of the most innovative new products, services and business leaders in the world.\n\nThe Edison Awards are focused on the innovators as much as the innovations \u2013 a unique distinction in the world of award programs.\u00a0 Open to innovative organizations across the globe, an Edison Award denotes significant value to the award winner and to the cause of innovation, highlighting the strong marketing value of an unbiased 3rd-party validation.\n\nAward winners represent \"game changing\" products and services, as well as excellence and leadership in innovation around four [https://edisonawards.com/criteria.php criteria]: Concept, Value, Delivery, and Impact.{{Infobox award\n| name = Edison Awards\n| current_awards =\n| image = Edison_Awards_Logo.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| description = Honoring excellence in new product and service development, marketing, human-centered design and innovation.\n| presenter = \n| country = [[United States]]\n| location =top paragraph\n| year = 1987\n| year2 =\n| website = http://www.edisonawards.com/\n}}  \n\n==The Edison Award's Mission==\nEdison Awards Mission Statement:  ''To be a leader in globally recognizing, honoring and fostering innovation and innovators to create a positive impact in the world. Our vision is continually guided by the legacy and vision of Thomas Edison and his Menlo Park team that successfully brought an unprecedented number of innovations to the market.''\n\n<br />\n== Edison Award Winners ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Edison Award Gala Opening and Winners Montage\n!List of Winners\n|-\n|\n|[https://edisonawards.com/winners2020.php 2020 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|2019 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|[http://www.edisonawards.com/winners2019.php 2019 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|2018 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|[http://www.edisonawards.com/winners2018.php 2018 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2-KwsVySfk 2017 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2017.php 2017 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixoVUtHCt1E 2016 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2016.php 2016 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sp_6p_vcnPs 2015 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2015.php 2015 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bUn0kTSjL18 2014 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2014.php 2014 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TmiyhGvMIeY 2013 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2013.php 2013 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SrlRctJS-Yc 2012 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|-\n|2011 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HyVM8EWtBUw 2010 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nd0F3Jx8JIM 2009 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|}<br />\n==Thomas Edison==\nThe Edison Awards are named after [[Thomas Edison|Thomas Alva Edison]] (1847-1931) whose extraordinary new product development methods garnered him 1,093 U.S. patents and made him a household name across the world as he pioneered five industries which transformed the world\u2014the incandescent electric light and the system of electrical power, the phonograph and recorded sound, the telephone transmitter, the storage battery, and movies and the motion-picture camera.   \n\n<br />\n\n== Categories ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |2020 Edison Award [https://edisonawards.com/edisonawardcategories.php Categories]\n|-\n|AEROSPACE INNOVATION\n|INDUSTRIAL DESIGN\n|-\n|APPLIED TECHNOLOGY\n|INNOVATIVE SERVICES\n|-\n|ATHLETICS, SPORTS & RECREATION\n|LIVING, WORKING & LEARNING ENVIRONMENTS\n|-\n|COLLECTIVE DISRUPTION\n|MEDIA, VISUAL COMMUNICATIONS & ENTERTAINMENT\n|-\n|CONSUMER ELECTRONICS & INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY\n|MEDICAL/DENTAL\n|-\n|CONSUMER GOODS\n|MATERIALS SCIENCE & ENGINEERING\n|-\n|ENERGY & SUSTAINABILITY\n|SOCIAL INNOVATION\n|-\n|HEALTH & WELLNESS\n|TRANSPORTATION & LOGISTICS\n|}\n<br />\n==Edison Achievement Award==\nThe [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward.php Edison Achievement Award] recognizes individuals who, through their careers, their leadership and their achievements, have distinguished themselves by making significant and lasting contributions to the world of innovation. The award is presented in the spring at the annual [https://edisonawards.com/highlights.php Edison Awards Ceremony and Gala].\n\n===Past Honorees===\nPast recipients of the Edison Achievement Award include:<ref>Damon Poeter, [https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2457459,00.asp Edison Awards Honor Elon Musk, Lenovo's Yang Yuanqing], ''PCMAG.com'', May 2, 2014</ref><ref>Miguel Helft, [http://fortune.com/2014/05/02/in-pursuit-of-innovation-a-milestone-for-lenovo/?section=magazines_fortune \"In pursuit of Innovation, a milestone for Lenovo\"], ''Fortune.com'', May 2, 2014</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |Edison Achievement Award Recipients\n|-\n|2019 - [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward/eaa-ginnirometty.php Ginni Rometty] \u2013 IBM\n|2009 \u2013 [[Susan Desmond-Hellmann]] \u2013 Genentech\n|-\n|2018 \u2013 [[Marillyn Hewson]] \u2013 Lockheed Martin\n|1999 \u2013 [[Ted Turner]] \u2013 Time Warner\n|-\n|2017 \u2013 [[Jeff Immelt]] \u2013 General Electric\n|1999 \u2013 Dale Morrison \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n|-\n|2017 \u2013 [[Astro Teller]] \u2013 X\n|1997 \u2013 Reuben Mark \u2013 Colgate-Palmolive\n|-\n|2016 \u2013 [[John T. Chambers|John Chambers]] \u2013 Cisco Systems, Inc.\n|1997 \u2013 [[Martha Stewart]] \u2013 MSL Omnimedia\n|-\n|2015 \u2013 [[Clayton M. Christensen]] \u2013 Harvard Business School\n|1996 \u2013 [[Douglas Ivester]] \u2013 Coca-Cola Company\n|-\n|2015 \u2013 [[Robert A. Lutz]] \u2013 General Motors Company\n|1996 \u2013 [[Nolan D. Archibald]] \u2013 Black & Decker\n|-\n|2014 \u2013 [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 Tesla, SpaceX\n|1995 \u2013 [[Robert Palmer (computer businessman)|Robert Palmer]] \u2013 Digital Corporation\n|-\n|2014 \u2013 [[Yang Yuanqing]] \u2013 Lenovo\n|1995 \u2013 Arthur Martinez \u2013 Sears, Roebuck & Co.\n|-\n|2013 \u2013 [[Paul E. Jacobs]] \u2013 Qualcomm\n|1994 \u2013 H. John Greeniaus \u2013 Nabisco, Inc.\n|-\n|2012 \u2013 [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]] \u2013 TED\n|1994 \u2013 Bert C. Roberts \u2013 MCI Corporation\n|-\n|2012 \u2013 [[Steve Jobs]] \u2013 Apple, Inc.\n|1993 \u2013 [[Bill_Marriott | J. Willard Marriott, Jr.]] \u2013 Marriott International\n|-\n|2011 \u2013 [[John S. Hendricks]] \u2013 Discovery Communications\n|1993 \u2013 [[Rich DeVos]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n|-\n|2011 \u2013 [[Alan Mulally]] \u2013 Ford Motor Company\n|1993 \u2013 [[Jay Van Andel]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n|-\n|2010 \u2013 [[Susan Hockfield]] \u2013 MIT\n|1993 \u2013 [[Raymond W. Smith]] \u2013 Bell Atlantic\n|-\n|2010 \u2013 [[A.G. Lafley]] \u2013 Procter & Gamble\n|1992 \u2013 [[William McGowan]] \u2013 MCI Corporation\n|-\n|2009 \u2013 [[David M. Kelley]] \u2013 IDEO\n|1991 \u2013 [[Frank Perdue]] \u2013 Perdue Farms\n|-\n|\n|1991 \u2013 Herb Baum \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n|}\n\n==Edison Awards Steering Committee==\nSenior executives with diverse marketing, scientific, and business backgrounds serve on the Edison Awards [https://edisonawards.com/steering.php Steering Committee], overseeing the reviews of innovations submitted from around the world. After thoroughly vetting each nomination, they select only those they believe merit consideration for an award, placing the approved applicants on a comprehensive ballot that is sent to over 3,000 experienced senior business executives worldwide.\n\nThe Steering Committee is also responsible for selecting the [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward.php Edison Achievement Award] recipient, selecting individuals who are on the cutting edge of innovation to receive this distinguished award.\n\n<br />\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<br />\n==External links==\n* [http://www.edisonawards.com/ Official Edison Awards website]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_overview.pdf Edison Awards Overview]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_snapshot.pdf Edison Awards Snapshot]\n\n[[Category:American awards]]\n[[Category:Engineering awards]]\n[[Category:Design awards]]\n[[Category:Business and industry awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Dutch award given for musical achievement|Edison Award}}\n{{advert|date=September 2018}}\nEstablished in 1987, the Edison Best New Product Awards\u2122 is an annual competition honoring excellence in innovation in a broad range of categories. \u00a0Known as \u201cthe Oscars of Innovation,\u201d the [https://edisonawards.com/ Edison Awards\u2122] have recognized and honored some of the most innovative new products, services and business leaders in the world.\n\nThe Edison Awards are focused on the innovators as much as the innovations \u2013 a unique distinction in the world of award programs.\u00a0 Open to innovative organizations across the globe, an Edison Award denotes significant value to the award winner and to the cause of innovation, highlighting the strong marketing value of an unbiased 3rd-party validation.\n\nAward winners represent \"game changing\" products and services, as well as excellence and leadership in innovation around four [https://edisonawards.com/criteria.php criteria]: Concept, Value, Delivery, and Impact.{{Infobox award\n| name = Edison Awards\n| current_awards =\n| image = Edison_Awards_Logo.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = \n| description = Honoring excellence in new product and service development, marketing, human-centered design and innovation.\n| presenter = \n| country = [[United States]]\n| location =top paragraph\n| year = 1987\n| year2 =\n| website = http://www.edisonawards.com/\n}}  \n\n==The Edison Award's Mission==\nEdison Awards Mission Statement:  ''To be a leader in globally recognizing, honoring and fostering innovation and innovators to create a positive impact in the world. Our vision is continually guided by the legacy and vision of Thomas Edison and his Menlo Park team that successfully brought an unprecedented number of innovations to the market.''\n\n<br />\n== Edison Award Winners ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Edison Award Gala Opening and Winners Montage\n!List of Winners\n|-\n|\n|[https://edisonawards.com/winners2020.php 2020 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|2019 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|[http://www.edisonawards.com/winners2019.php 2019 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|2018 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|[http://www.edisonawards.com/winners2018.php 2018 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2-KwsVySfk 2017 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2017.php 2017 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ixoVUtHCt1E 2016 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2016.php 2016 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sp_6p_vcnPs 2015 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2015.php 2015 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bUn0kTSjL18 2014 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2014.php 2014 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TmiyhGvMIeY 2013 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|[http://edisonawards.com/winners2013.php 2013 Edison Award Winners]\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SrlRctJS-Yc 2012 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|-\n|2011 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HyVM8EWtBUw 2010 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|-\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nd0F3Jx8JIM 2009 Edison Award Gala Opening and Winner Montage]\n|\n|}<br />\n==Thomas Edison==\nThe Edison Awards are named after [[Thomas Edison|Thomas Alva Edison]] (1847-1931) whose extraordinary new product development methods garnered him 1,093 U.S. patents and made him a household name across the world as he pioneered five industries which transformed the world\u2014the incandescent electric light and the system of electrical power, the phonograph and recorded sound, the telephone transmitter, the storage battery, and movies and the motion-picture camera.   \n\n<br />\n\n== Categories ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! colspan=\"2\" |2020 Edison Award [https://edisonawards.com/edisonawardcategories.php Categories]\n|-\n|AEROSPACE INNOVATION\n|INDUSTRIAL DESIGN\n|-\n|APPLIED TECHNOLOGY\n|INNOVATIVE SERVICES\n|-\n|ATHLETICS, SPORTS & RECREATION\n|LIVING, WORKING & LEARNING ENVIRONMENTS\n|-\n|COLLECTIVE DISRUPTION\n|MEDIA, VISUAL COMMUNICATIONS & ENTERTAINMENT\n|-\n|CONSUMER ELECTRONICS & INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY\n|MEDICAL/DENTAL\n|-\n|CONSUMER GOODS\n|MATERIALS SCIENCE & ENGINEERING\n|-\n|ENERGY & SUSTAINABILITY\n|SOCIAL INNOVATION\n|-\n|HEALTH & WELLNESS\n|TRANSPORTATION & LOGISTICS\n|}\n<br />\n==Edison Achievement Award==\nThe [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward.php Edison Achievement Award] recognizes individuals who, through their careers, their leadership and their achievements, have distinguished themselves by making significant and lasting contributions to the world of innovation. The award is presented in the spring at the annual [https://edisonawards.com/highlights.php Edison Awards Ceremony and Gala].\n\n===Past Honorees===\nPast recipients of the Edison Achievement Award include:<ref>Damon Poeter, [https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2457459,00.asp Edison Awards Honor Elon Musk, Lenovo's Yang Yuanqing], ''PCMAG.com'', May 2, 2014</ref><ref>Miguel Helft, [http://fortune.com/2014/05/02/in-pursuit-of-innovation-a-milestone-for-lenovo/?section=magazines_fortune \"In pursuit of Innovation, a milestone for Lenovo\"], ''Fortune.com'', May 2, 2014</ref>\n* 2019 - [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward/eaa-ginnirometty.php Ginni Rometty] \u2013 IBM\n*2018 \u2013 [[Marillyn Hewson]] \u2013 Lockheed Martin\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Jeff Immelt]] \u2013 General Electric\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Astro Teller]] \u2013 X\n* 2016 \u2013 [[John T. Chambers|John Chambers]] \u2013 Cisco Systems, Inc.\n* 2015 \u2013 [[Clayton M. Christensen]] \u2013 Harvard Business School\n* 2015 \u2013 [[Robert A. Lutz]] \u2013 General Motors Company \n* 2014 \u2013 [[Yang Yuanqing]] \u2013 Lenovo\n* 2014 \u2013 [[Elon Musk]] \u2013 Tesla, SpaceX\n* 2013 \u2013 [[Paul E. Jacobs]] \u2013 Qualcomm\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Chris Anderson (entrepreneur)|Chris Anderson]] \u2013 TED\n* 2012 \u2013 [[Steve Jobs]] \u2013 Apple, Inc.\n* 2011 \u2013 [[John S. Hendricks]] \u2013 Discovery Communications\n* 2011 \u2013 [[Alan Mulally]] \u2013 Ford Motor Company\n* 2010 \u2013 [[Susan Hockfield]] \u2013 MIT\n* 2010 \u2013 [[A.G. Lafley]] \u2013 Procter & Gamble\n* 2009 \u2013 [[David M. Kelley]] \u2013 IDEO\n* 2009 \u2013 [[Susan Desmond-Hellmann]] \u2013 Genentech\n* 1999 \u2013 [[Ted Turner]] \u2013 Time Warner\n* 1999 \u2013 Dale Morrison \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n* 1997 \u2013 Reuben Mark \u2013 Colgate-Palmolive\n* 1997 \u2013 [[Martha Stewart]] \u2013 MSL Omnimedia\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Douglas Ivester]] \u2013 Coca-Cola Company\n* 1996 \u2013 [[Nolan D. Archibald]] \u2013 Black & Decker\n* 1995 \u2013 [[Robert Palmer (computer businessman)|Robert Palmer]] \u2013 Digital Corporation\n* 1995 \u2013 Arthur Martinez \u2013 Sears, Roebuck & Co.\n* 1994 \u2013 H. John Greeniaus \u2013 Nabisco, Inc.\n* 1994 \u2013 Bert C. Roberts \u2013 MCI Corporation\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Bill_Marriott | J. Willard Marriott, Jr.]] \u2013 Marriott International\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Rich DeVos]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Jay Van Andel]] \u2013 Amway Corporation\n* 1993 \u2013 [[Raymond W. Smith]] \u2013 Bell Atlantic\n* 1992 \u2013 [[William McGowan]] \u2013 MCI Corporation\n* 1991 \u2013 [[Frank Perdue]] \u2013 Perdue Farms\n* 1991 \u2013 Herb Baum \u2013 Campbell Soup Co.\n\n<br />\n==Edison Awards Steering Committee==\nSenior executives with diverse marketing, scientific, and business backgrounds serve on the Edison Awards [https://edisonawards.com/steering.php Steering Committee], overseeing the reviews of innovations submitted from around the world. After thoroughly vetting each nomination, they select only those they believe merit consideration for an award, placing the approved applicants on a comprehensive ballot that is sent to over 3,000 experienced senior business executives worldwide.\n\nThe Steering Committee is also responsible for selecting the [https://edisonawards.com/achievementaward.php Edison Achievement Award] recipient, selecting individuals who are on the cutting edge of innovation to receive this distinguished award.\n\n<br />\n==See also==\n\n* [[List of engineering awards]]\n\n<br />\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}<br />\n==External links==\n* [http://www.edisonawards.com/ Official Edison Awards website]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_overview.pdf Edison Awards Overview]\n*[https://edisonawards.com/downloads/EdisonAwards_snapshot.pdf Edison Awards Snapshot]\n\n[[Category:American awards]]\n[[Category:Engi